result.execSummary:
The defendant Clayton Jc Selsing was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture/Deliver Heroin (<3g) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(d)1.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Substance Abuse Program but not until served at least 3 years of prison.

superMiscConds.notes: Jointly and severally due.  Defendant stipulates to restitution amount.

Outstanding financial obligations shall be paid from all prison wages at a rate of 25% and the balance due as a condition of extended supervision.  If extended supervision is revoked or will discharge with financial obligations owing, a judgment shall be entered.
Defendant shall obtain and maintain full time employment or schooling or combination thereof to equal full time.

Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety.

Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol or controlled substance without a valid prescription and then take medication as prescribed.

Defendant shall have no contact with any members of Jeffrey E.'s family or extended family.

Defendant shall have no contact with Tyler S., Twan P., Marlayna J., Cassie E., Dustin S., Holl S., Mari S. or Randal L.

Defendant shall have no contact with drug users or drug sellers.

Defendant shall participate in all counseling and/or treatment programs directed by the probation agent and comply with treatment recommendations.

Defendant shall provide a DNA sample.

Defendant shall submit to random drug/urine screens.

Defendant shall pay any supervision fees as determined by the Department of Corrections.
